<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-6">What is Permaculture?</h1>

<p class="text-lg mb-6">
  Permaculture is a holistic design system for creating sustainable human environments by mimicking natural ecosystems. It integrates principles of ecology, regenerative agriculture, and community resilience to develop systems that are self-sustaining and resource-efficient.
</p>

<p class="text-lg mb-6">
  Permaculture emphasizes the use of renewable resources, biodiversity, and ethical care for the earth, people, and future generations. Its practices include water management, soil restoration, companion planting, and energy-efficient living. By observing and working with nature, permaculture aims to harmonize human activity with the environment, fostering abundance and resilience in food production, shelter, and community systems. It’s a framework for regenerative and sustainable living.
</p>

<div class="border-t border-gray-300 my-8"></div>

<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-4">How is Permaculture Different from Regular Agriculture?</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">1. Design Philosophy</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>🌿 Permaculture:</strong> Focuses on designing ecosystems that mimic natural processes, aiming for long-term sustainability and self-regeneration.
      <br>
      <strong>🚜 Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Often prioritizes maximizing short-term yields, sometimes at the expense of soil health and ecosystem balance.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">2. Diversity vs. Monoculture</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>🌼 Permaculture:</strong> Promotes biodiversity through polycultures and companion planting to create resilient ecosystems.
      <br>
      <strong>🌾 Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Relies heavily on monocultures, which can lead to pest outbreaks, soil depletion, and dependency on chemical inputs.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">3. Soil Health</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>🌱 Permaculture:</strong> Builds soil health through practices like composting, mulching, and minimal tilling.
      <br>
      <strong>🔄 Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Often depletes soil nutrients through intensive tillage and chemical fertilizers, leading to erosion and degradation.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">4. Energy Use</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>☀️ Permaculture:</strong> Utilizes renewable energy sources and passive energy designs.
      <br>
      <strong>⛽ Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Often depends on fossil fuels for machinery, irrigation, and synthetic inputs.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">5. Water Management</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>💧 Permaculture:</strong> Implements water-conserving techniques such as swales, rainwater harvesting, and contour planting.
      <br>
      <strong>🚰 Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Frequently relies on large-scale irrigation systems, which can lead to water wastage and depletion of local water sources.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">6. Ethics and Sustainability</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>🌍 Permaculture:</strong> Operates on ethical principles: care for the earth, care for people, and fair share of resources.
      <br>
      <strong>📈 Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Typically driven by economic priorities, sometimes overlooking environmental and social impacts.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold">7. Inputs and Waste</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>♻️ Permaculture:</strong> Seeks to minimize external inputs by recycling nutrients and resources within the system.
      <br>
      <strong>🚮 Traditional Agriculture:</strong> Often depends on synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and herbicides, which can create waste and pollution.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="border-t border-gray-300 my-8"></div>

<p class="text-lg">
  In essence, <strong>permaculture</strong> works with nature to create regenerative systems, while <strong>traditional agriculture</strong> often imposes human-centered systems on the land, which can degrade natural resources over time.
</p>
